December 24, 2013
An Approach that Works


With over 20 years of experience in law, finance, venture capital, and business development, Jon Sabes is the cofounder and chief executive officer of GWG Holdings, Inc., in Minneapolis, Minnesota. In addition to his successful career, Jon Sabes is an active participant in endurance athletic events, such as Ironman Wisconsin 2013, his third Ironman event. Writing about his participation in Ironman Wisconsin 2013, Mr. Sabes writes about his approach to these types of events: “You have understand that I am an amateur athlete who likes to participate in outdoor endurance events, in other words, it’s a hobby. That means I don’t do not compete for money (I don’t make my living doing this) and my goal is not necessarily to stand on the podium in my age group (although that’s always nice if it were to happen). I am not out there to set a course record, but rather my goal is to be physically and mentally prepared to complete Ironman any day of the week, any month of the year, at a solid weekend warrior pace (as I call it) while being grateful that I can. That is my approach, it’s not for everyone, but it works for me. This approach leads me not to rush through transitions, and smile, acknowledge and thank volunteers and spectators who help me throughout day. This is exactly what I did at Ironman Wisconsin 2013. This approach that always feels good, no matter what my time or physical condition. Being grateful is where I like to be mentally: Grateful for my health and the opportunity to participate. For me, Ironman is all about being who I want to be, both physically and mentally, and actualizing for 12ish hours during the event (some might call it active meditation).”


