November 18, 2013
Basic Facts about Bonds


A finance professional with more than two decades of experience, Jon Sabes serves as chief executive officer of GWG Holdings, Inc., and MedFinance. The founder of both companies, Jon Sabes applies his knowledge of venture capital, financial transactions, law, business development, and structured finance to realize an optimal outcome for the businesses he oversees.Structured finance offers a unique ability to issue debt securities to banks, financial institutions, and individual investors. Debt securities in structured finance possess priority as creditors to specific pools of assets; this status means that they receive payment before shareholders and other creditors. Depending on the type of debt securities an investor holds and the security pledged to support it, some debt holders rank higher in repayment precedence than others.Structured finance techniques generally enable firms to obtain access to more capital at lower interest because they are backed by actual assets or collateral that produce cash flows, or that which can be traded or sold to repay debt holders. These assets represent the opportunity to collect funds from issuers or courts under well established legal constructs. When a corporation issues debt securities using structured finance techniques, the assets and the legal documentation governing the rights to collateral are of primary importance. Using structured finance, a company’s credit rating is not as relevant to the determination of the interest rates as is the collateral as a source of repayment in satisfaction of the debt.


Filed under debt bonds Jon Sabes 



