November 5, 2013
SEC Registration Basics


Jon Sabes holds the position of chief executive officer of Minneapolis-based GWG Holdings, Inc., and of MedFinance, both of which he established nearly 10 years ago, One of the companies, GWG Holdings, Inc., has filed a registration statement under the Securities Act of 1933, also known as the truth in securities law. The Securities Act of 1933 strived to provide protection to investors by creating transparency about the financial health of organizations issuing securities. Overseen by the United States Securities and Exchange Commission, the Securities Act of 1933 requires organizations to disclose crucial financial information upon mandatory registration of securities. Registration with the United States Securities and Exchange Commission entails reporting descriptions about GWG Holdings, Inc.’s business and property, meticulous details about the securities themselves, independently audited financial statements, and depictions of the company’s management. The United States Securities and Exchange Commission makes all registrations available to potential investors and the public via EDGAR, or the Electronic Data-Gathering, Analysis, and Retrieval system. The system executes automated collections, validation, cataloging, and acceptance of registration data. Although federal regulations require registration for most securities, exemptions include transactions involving private offerings, intrastate offerings, and municipal securities.


