October 28, 2013
Triathlon Hydration Tips


Jon Sabes is co-founder of GWG Holdings, Inc. With over 20 years’ experience in finance, venture capital, law, banking, and more, Jon Sabes has founded a business that provides a valuable service to consumers who own life insurance but no longer can afford their life insurance or no longer have the need for the which the life insurance was purchased. In addition to his career, Sabes is an amature endurance athlete who regularly competes in triathlons.For triathletes, creating a logical hydration and nutrition strategy for race day can mean the difference between success and failure. The level of exertion endurance triathletes experience requires them to replenish their body with vital fluids and nutrients. Experts suggest accomplishing this in a number of ways. -Try fluid replacement drinks. Athletes should test different flavors and brands weeks before the race to ensure it will not upset their stomach. Try to stay away from products whose ingredients you cannot understand. Choose a drink with the right balance of sodium, potassium, and carbohydrate. Tough exercise requires the replenishment of electrolytes for adequate recovery. Not getting enough can spell disaster for the triathlete. -Try real food. Eating real food, as opposed to multicolored gels and chewables is smart. Your body is used to eating real food and can get nutrients from foods that include avacados, apples, oranges, banannas as part of their construction. This year I employed a new technique, something I learned from last year when I went to grab my whole grain, almond butter, avocado sandwich on my bike – it had turned to mush – as well as the bag of whole foods sweet potatoes – but I just squeezed the bag and I ate it like space man food It was yummy and my body liked it and it was easier to consumer in mash form So that is what I do, real food mush bags.In the end, be creative, but try to stay clean with your eating. Eating clean is your bodies best friend when it comes to hydration and nutrition during exercise. Also, experiment with different levels of intake before, during and after exercise. Use the weeks leading up to the race to will help you find the right hydration and nutrition strategy for your body.


