October 15, 2013
Tips for Proper Running Technique


Jon Sabes is a highly experienced executive in the financial industry. With more than 20 years of service, he has worked with a variety of businesses in developing their financing capabilities. Apart from his professional pursuits, Jon Sabes is an avid swimmer, biker, and runner who enjoys endurance athletics. Long distance runners should focus on their form in order to improve their running speed and avoid injury. Two major considerations in proper runner’s form are the arms position and torso activation. The arms should be only swing forward and back in a motion that is parallel with the body and with the elbows bent at a 90-degree angle. Many runners mistakenly swim their arms side to side across their torso, which increases stress on the spine and does not add to the forward momentum of running. When the forearms become tense, or fists begin to clench, runners should drop them to the side and shake them out to release all tension. Try focusing on your fingers - pinching them together to create a tension which you can direct your focus towards. The head and shoulders influence the position of the torso. When the head is up and the shoulders are low and loose with the back straight, the runner’s torso position will promote optimal oxygen intake. The lungs will then be free to expand to full capacity. A slight lean forward allows gravity to work in your favor, helping propel you forward through the air. Try focusing on your tail bone - allowing it to slide back and tucking it under to feel the change in your hip position.Proper running technique will ensure maximum performance with minimal injury to the body. When you run, see how long you can focus on aspects of form alone - holding your concentration on form can improve your running and pass the time quickly as the miles go by.


Filed under Jon Sabes financial industry runners 







